1. Attributes
Explanation:
Attributes in HTML are used to configure elements and provide additional information about them. 
They are added to the opening tag of an element and look like this: attribute_name="value".

Examples of attributes:
id — assigns a unique identifier to an element. // задає 
class — allows grouping elements for styling or JavaScript.
href — hyperlink for the <a> tag.
src — path to an image for the <img> tag.
alt — text for an image if it fails to load.

Task:
Create an HTML document with a hyperlink that has the href and target="_blank" attributes.
Add an image with src and alt attributes.
Use id and class attributes to create an element that can be styled using CSS.

2. Tables
Explanation:
Tables in HTML are used to display data in a tabular format. Key tags:
<table> — defines a table.
<tr> — table row.
<td> — table cell (regular).
<th> — table header cell (bold text, centered).
<caption> — table title.
Attributes:
border — adds borders to the table.
colspan — merges cells horizontally.
rowspan — merges cells vertically.

Task:
Create a table with three rows and two columns.
Add headers in the first row using <th>.
Add a border="1" attribute to the table.
Merge two cells in one row using colspan.

3. Forms
Explanation:
Forms are used to collect data from users. Key tags:
<form> — container for the form.
<input> — input field (text, password, button, etc.).
<textarea> — multi-line text field.
<select> and <option> — dropdown list.
<button> — button.

Attributes:
action — path to the script that processes form data.
method — method of data submission (GET or POST).
type — type of input (text, password, submit, checkbox, etc.).
name — field identifier sent to the server.
placeholder — placeholder text in a field.

Task:
Create a form with a text field, a password field, and a submit button.
Add a dropdown list with three options.
Use the placeholder attribute for hints in the text field.